post_text: Thanks for sharing your first-day photos Jamestown Upper! It was terrific hearing kids in the halls and seeing them in the classrooms. We are off to a fantastic start of 2020-2021.
shared_text:
Jamestown Elementary
August 24 at 3:48 PM ¬∑

It was awesome to welcome your kids back to Jamestown Upper. Our staff was so eager to be back with them and there are so many positives to take from day #1. You can see students here taking one of their safe mask breaks while socially distancing outside. The wall of staff pictures with masks on and off helps our students to recognize us either way. Our staff did a great job of cleaning and ensuring safety for students! #JamestownPride

post_text: Thank you Todd! #FireUpGoEagles
shared_text:
Todd Groothuis
August 23 at 3:21 PM ¬∑

As I begin year twenty-something of education tomorrow, I think every parent of a Hudsonville Public School student needs to hear this: Don‚Äôt worry! You are entrusting your children to some of the greatest human beings I have ever met. Your children will be loved, taken care of, and taught. I have seen the numbers; I know the predictions. But I believe this will be the greatest accomplishment in the history of HPS. It seems like since this has started all we have done is lose. What if tomorrow we start winning?

post_text: We encourage you to check in on your own mental health status as well as your friends, family, and neighbors. The ongoing ordeal of the COVID-19 pandemic is putting significant stress on all of us. Most of us are feeling frustrated, confused, and anxious. It is vital to take a moment, take a deep breath, and think about ways you can remain calm, remain positive, and be resilient. If you are feeling overwhelmed, reach out to someone and talk about your concerns. CALL 2-1-1 is an excellent place to help you find mental health services and resources in our community. You can also call the CMHOC Access Center at 877-588-4357 for assistance in finding mental health services or our 24-hour Crisis Line for emergencies at 866-512-4357.
shared_text:
Community Mental Health of Ottawa County
July 17 at 10:01 AM ¬∑

We encourage you to check in on your own mental health status as well as your friends, family, and neighbors. The ongoing ordeal of the COVID-19 pandemic is putting significant stress on all of us. Most of us are feeling frustrated, confused, and anxious. It is very important to take a moment, take a deep breath, and think about ways you can remain calm, remain positive, and be resilient. If you are feeling overwhelmed, reach out to someone and talk about your concerns. CALL 2-1-1 is an excellent place to help you find mental health services and resources in our community. You can also call the CMHOC Access Center at 877-588-4357 for assistance in finding mental health services or our 24-hour Crisis Line for emergencies at 866-512-4357.

post_text:
From the City of Hudsonville...

Your water bill is wrong.

You read that right.

Unfortunately, ALL the water bills got printed with the water usage of a large downtown account, which means when you open up your water bill, it's going to say that you owe $3,000.

Please disregard this version of your water bill. The printer will be re-printing the correct version and re-mailing those.

Thanks for your patience on this!
shared_text:
City of Hudsonville Government
July 6 at 11:46 AM ¬∑

A statement from Kent Communications Inc (KCI):

KCI recently printed and mailed The City of Hudsonville‚Äôs Water/Sewer Bills.

There was a clerical error made by KCI on these bills which is no fault of City of Hudsonville. KCI takes full responsibly of this error made and has added quality control checks to help so it does not happen again.

Your revised bill is being mailed out July 6, 2020. We apologize for the inconvenience this has caused to the residents and the City of Hudsonville

shared_text:
HOLLANDSENTINEL.COM

post_text: During a typical summer, a break from school is associated with a sense of freedom, relaxation, play, and leisure. Learning often pauses for students, with studies showing that many students experience summer slide and that summer slide is more pronounced among working-class and poor children than among middle-class children. Many educators have advocated for additional learning opportunities to mitigate summer slide and to increase summer learning. This year, more than ever before, summer learning opportunities will be essential for students. go.aws/3gyi8gL

post_text:
These are tough times; there is just no way around that fact. We have to try to maintain our physical health during a global pandemic, while also helping to manage our family's health. We have to work remotely, or navigate unemployment, homeschool our kids, and spend a lot of time searching for food and toilet paper. There are not enough hours in the day it seems, and the days blur as our time at home goes on.

BUT we have to also take care of ourselves, both physically and mentally. This is a crucial step not only for ourselves but for ALL the people who depend on us. The minutes you spend on YOU are just as important as ALL the time spent on them. And we all know that finding time for this isn't easy in the best of times, much less now. Sign up for this virtual town hall meeting, you'll be glad you did! momentumcentergh.org/covid-town-hall
text:
These are tough times; there is just no way around that fact. We have to try to maintain our physical health during a global pandemic, while also helping to manage our family's health. We have to work remotely, or navigate unemployment, homeschool our kids, and spend a lot of time searching for food and toilet paper. There are not enough hours in the day it seems, and the days blur as our time at home goes on.

BUT we have to also take care of ourselves, both physically and mentally. This is a crucial step not only for ourselves but for ALL the people who depend on us. The minutes you spend on YOU are just as important as ALL the time spent on them. And we all know that finding time for this isn't easy in the best of times, much less now. Sign up for this virtual town hall meeting, you'll be glad you did! momentumcentergh.org/covid-town-hall

post_text: Congratulations! Two Hudsonville Careerline Tech Center (CTC) students in the Graphic Design program were awarded top prizes for their entries in the 32nd annual North American International Auto Show (NAIAS) Poster Contest. Hudsonville High School junior, Avery Brodie, received the Designer's Best in Show Award, and junior Halle Flowers from Hudsonville High School won first place in the 11th Grade Award. While the NAIAS Auto Show was canceled due to the COVID-19 pandemic, the poster contest remained open for students in grades 10-12 and received approximately 750 entries from 58 Michigan schools. #FireUpGoEagles #OAISD #DMTOttawa

post_text: Where there's a WILL, there's a WAY! A Bauer family shared how they are continuing with our S.O.A.R. program at home.
shared_text:
Bauer Elementary School
April 15 at 4:47 PM ¬∑

Where there's a WILL there's a WAY! A Bauer family shared how they are continuing with our S.O.A.R. program at home.

Mom wrote: "The kids helped me come up with this so I went off what they told me they do at school. They earn S.O.A.R. cards for being kind, doing chores, doing their lessons, etc. Three soar cards equals a golden ticket. Golden tickets could be redeemed for extra stories, a special activity or anything of that sort. My kids use them as "Amazon Dollars." At the end of the week they can spend them or save them to get something worth more. Trying to keep the sibling rivalry to a minimum and continue S.O.A.R.-ing at home. I hope maybe this can help other families motivate their kiddos too."
text:

They earn S.O.A.R. cards for being kind, doing chores, doing their lessons, etc. Three soar cards equals a golden ticket. Golden tickets could be redeemed for extra stories, a special activity or anything of that sort. My kids use them as "Amazon Dollars." At the end of the week they can spend them or save them to get something worth more. Trying to keep the sibling rivalry to a minimum and continue S.O.A.R.-ing at home. I hope maybe this can help other families motivate their kiddos too."

post_text: Autism affects approximately 1 out of every 150 children around the world. It is a neural development disorder that affects their ability to socialize normally by impacting their abilities to utilize verbal and non-verbal communication. Since 2012, there has been a 30% increase in the number of children being affected with autism, and World Autism Awareness Day helps to bring awareness to this growing health concern. #AutismDay

The robotics program will be hosting an event on Monday, March 23, from 7:00 - 8:30 pm at the Freshman Campus Cafeteria / Commons area.

We will be recognizing our teams that made it to the state tournament and our seniors that will be graduating this year. We will also be sharing the state of our program and plans for the 2020-21 season, which starts in May. If you are newly interested in the program or a robotics veteran, we would like to invite you to join the celebration. We will have robots and drones on display and opportunities for you to learn about the program.

Hudsonville Robotics is open to HPS students from grades 4 to 12. You are welcome to share this message with other interested families.

post_text:
Congratulations, Kayla Wolma, for being chosen for a Michigan High School Athletic Association scholarship! Each of the scholarship recipients will be honored at a halftime ceremony, March 28, at the Breslin Student Events Center in East Lansing.

Students applying for the Scholar-Athlete Award must be carrying at least a 3.5 (on a 4.0 scale) grade-point average and have previously won a letter in a varsity sport in which the Michigan High School Athletic Association sponsors a postseason tournament. Other requirements for the applicants were to show active participation in other school and community activities and produce an essay on the importance of sportsmanship in educational athletics. #FireUpGoEagles
